The final bell rang.
Students began packing their bags, chairs scraping loudly against the floor as conversations filled the room.
Kaito stayed seated.
Same as always.
He waited.
Not for anything in particular… just out of habit.
“…You’re not leaving?”
That voice again.
Kaito didn’t need to turn around.
“…Eventually.”
Hana leaned over his desk, resting her chin on her hand.
“You always wait until everyone leaves?”
“It’s quieter.”
“Wow… you really hate people, huh?”
“I don’t hate them.”
He paused.
“…I just don’t need them.”
Hana smiled slightly.
“Then what about me?”
Kaito didn’t answer.
And for some reason…
She didn’t push it this time.
A few minutes later, the classroom was empty.
Kaito finally stood up, slinging his bag over his shoulder.
As he walked toward the door—
Hana followed.
Of course she did.
“You live nearby?” she asked.
“Yes.”
“Same.”
“…Okay.”
“…That’s it?”
“What else do you want me to say?”
She puffed her cheeks slightly.
“You’re so dry.”
“And you talk too much.”
“Balance.”
They stepped outside.
The sky was painted in soft orange, the sun slowly sinking behind the buildings.
Students passed by them in groups, laughing, talking, living their normal school lives.
Kaito walked slightly ahead.
Hana walked beside him anyway.
For a while…
Neither of them spoke.
Just footsteps.
Side by side.
Then—
“Hey.”
“…What?”
“Are we friends?”
Kaito stopped walking.
That question again.
So simple.
So unnecessary.
“…No.”
Hana blinked.
“…Oh.”
He continued walking.
“…We just sit next to each other.”
A pause.
Then—
“…That’s all.”
She didn’t reply immediately.
And for the first time since they met…
Hana was quiet.
“…Then I’ll change that.”
Kaito glanced at her.
“What?”
She smiled.
“I’ll make you call me your friend.”
“…Sounds like a waste of time.”
“Maybe.”
She looked forward, eyes soft.
“But I don’t mind.”
They reached a small intersection.
A split in the road.
Kaito stopped.
“I go this way.”
Hana nodded.
“Me too.”
“…Of course you do.”
She laughed.
As they walked again, slower this time—
Hana spoke quietly.
“Hey… Kaito.”
It was the first time she said his name.
“…What?”
“If I stop talking one day…”
He looked at her.
“…Would you notice?”
The question lingered in the air.
Light.
But strangely heavy.
Kaito looked forward again.
“…Yeah.”
Hana blinked.
“…Really?”
“…It’d be quieter.”
A pause.
“…Too quiet.”
She smiled.
Not the loud, playful one.
A softer one.
“…Good.”
The sun dipped lower.
Their shadows stretched along the road.
Walking side by side.
Not quite friends.
Not strangers anymore either.
For the first time in a long time—
Kaito didn’t feel like rushing home.